text: APHIS works to safeguard American agricul-
label: BODY

text: ture by keeping destructive foreign pests and
label: BODY

text: diseases out of the United States. Should an
label: BODY

text: exotic disease threaten U.S. borders, it’s
label: BODY

text: APHIS’ role to combat the threat and pre-
label: BODY

text: vent an outbreak. By ensuring the health and
label: BODY

text: well-being of animals and plants nationwide,
label: BODY

text: APHIS helps improve agricultural productiv-
label: BODY

text: ity and competitiveness and contributes to
label: BODY

text: the national economy and the public health.
label: BODY

text: APHIS’ dedicated workforce strives to meet
label: BODY

text: the needs of an ever-expanding customer
label: BODY

text: base. We use state-of-the-art technology to
label: BODY

text: keep up with trends in agriculture and inter-
label: BODY

text: national trade as well as other pertinent
label: BODY

text: issues. All of our work enhances the United
label: BODY

text: States’ ability to buy and sell agricultural
label: BODY

text: products in the international marketplace,
label: BODY

text: fortiﬁes our abundant, safe, and diverse food
label: BODY

text: supply, and contributes to the health of U.S.
label: BODY

text: public and private lands.
label: BODY

text: Global Trade Agreements
label: BODY

text: Several global trade agreements help
label: BODY

text: APHIS to carry out its mission, the most
label: BODY

text: important of which are the North American
label: BODY

text: Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) and the
label: BODY

text: World Trade Organization (WTO) Sanitary
label: BODY

text: and Phytosanitary (SPS) Agreement, the suc-
label: BODY

text: cessor to the General Agreement on Tariffs
label: BODY

text: and Trade (GATT). Both have helped the
label: BODY

text: United States become more competitive in
label: BODY

text: the international trade arena, especially in
label: BODY

text: the area of agriculture.
label: BODY

text: This growing interest in agricultural trade
label: BODY

text: has created a more visible role for APHIS and
label: BODY

text: expanded our mission to ensure that new
label: BODY

text: trade opportunities beneﬁt the United States
label: BODY

text: without creating new threats from harmful
label: BODY

text: exotic pests and diseases. APHIS is delegated
label: BODY

text: as the primary negotiator for SPS-related
label: BODY

text: trade issues. In that role, APHIS has the
label: BODY

text: responsibility for regulating the importation
label: BODY

text: of food and agricultural commodities into
label: BODY

text: the United States as well as establishing SPS
label: BODY

text: requirements that set the boundaries for safe
label: BODY

text: international agricultural trade. The need for
label: BODY

text: such SPS requirements is fully recognized by
label: BODY

text: NAFTA and the WTO.
label: BODY

text: NAFTA, a trilateral trade pact between the
label: BODY

text: United States, Canada, and Mexico, went into
label: BODY

text: effect in January 1994. The GATT was estab-
label: BODY

text: lished in the wake of World War II, and its
label: BODY

text: successor organization, the WTO, was cre-
label: BODY

text: ated in 1995 after a series of trade negotia-
label: BODY

text: tions known as the Uruguay Round.
label: BODY

text: Collectively, the WTO’s more than 140 mem-
label: BODY

text: ber countries account for more than 90 per-
label: BODY

text: cent of world trade. Decisions are made
label: BODY

text: based on the consensus of the entire WTO
label: BODY

text: membership.
label: BODY

text: During NAFTA and WTO negotiations, coun-
label: BODY

text: tries embarked on a historic effort to reform
label: BODY

text: agricultural trade. Under both agreements,
label: BODY

text: countries are required to base their SPS
label: BODY

text: measures on scientiﬁc evidence. In short,
label: BODY

text: countries are now required to scientiﬁcally
label: BODY

text: justify their reasons for impeding the free
label: BODY

text: 2 APHIS in the Global Trade Arena
label: BODY

text: Protecting American agriculture is the
label: H2

text: basic charge of the U.S. Department of
label: H2

text: Agriculture’s (USDA) Animal and Plant
label: H2

text: Health Inspection Service (APHIS).
label: H2

text: APHIS has employees stationed across
label: H2

text: the country and around the world to
label: H2

text: accomplish this mission.
label: H2

text: ﬂow of trade. With the reductions in quotas
label: BODY

text: and tariffs that are a result of WTO and
label: BODY

text: NAFTA, there is a greater potential for coun-
label: BODY

text: tries to use pests and diseases as artiﬁcial
label: BODY

text: barriers to trade. In order to exclude agricul-
label: BODY

text: tural products presented for importation, a
label: BODY

text: country must be able to scientiﬁcally docu-
label: BODY

text: ment that allowing such importation would
label: BODY

text: create an unacceptable risk of introducing
label: BODY

text: foreign pests or disease. To be designated as
label: BODY

text: quarantine signiﬁcant, a pest or disease must
label: BODY

text: not exist in the importing country or be
label: BODY

text: present only in a limited area that is under
label: BODY

text: ofﬁcial control.
label: BODY

text: NAFTA and WTO requirements for risk
label: BODY

text: assessments are intended to make countries’
label: BODY

text: SPS regulations more transparent and scien-
label: BODY

text: tiﬁcally based. Countries also are required to
label: BODY

text: be consistent in their risk management prac-
label: BODY

text: tices. Agricultural ofﬁcials cannot treat one
label: BODY

text: country different from another when the
label: BODY

text: importation of their goods would result in
label: BODY

text: the same pest risk. It is important to note,
label: BODY

text: however, that NAFTA and WTO clearly recog-
label: BODY

text: nize the rights of countries to set their own
label: BODY

text: levels of protection.
label: BODY

text: Regionalization
label: BODY

text: In addition, the WTO and NAFTA commit
label: BODY

text: countries to recognizing disease- and pest-
label: BODY

text: free areas within a country even if a particu-
label: BODY

text: lar pest or disease exists elsewhere in the
label: BODY

text: nation. This concept is perhaps the most sig-
label: BODY

text: niﬁcant policy and regulatory issue facing
label: BODY

text: APHIS and our trade partners. It has, how-
label: BODY

text: ever, created new opportunities for the
label: BODY

text: United States, as well as other countries that
label: BODY

text: may have a pest in one region but be free of
label: BODY

text: it elsewhere.
label: BODY

text: The concept of regionalization is founded on
label: BODY

text: the longstanding idea that import require-
label: BODY

text: ments should be based on geography and sci-
label: BODY

text: ence rather than on politics. The political
label: BODY

text: borders between countries and delimiting
label: BODY

text: states within a country are invisible; geo-
label: BODY

text: graphic boundaries, such as mountains and
label: BODY

text: rivers, are not. Pests and diseases must be
label: BODY

text: able to travel in order to spread. If the path is
label: BODY

text: blocked by a mountain range down the mid-
label: BODY

text: dle of a country, then the disease is naturally
label: BODY

text: conﬁned to one side of that country.
label: BODY

text: The states of Sonora and Yucatan in Mexico
label: BODY

text: are prime examples. While other regions
label: BODY

text: in Mexico still have outbreaks of classical
label: BODY

text: swine fever (CSF), the prevalence of the
label: BODY

text: disease in Sonora and Yucatan is low. Based
label: BODY

text: on the principle of regionalization and a risk
label: BODY

text: analysis, the United States accepts imports of
label: BODY

text: fresh (chilled or frozen) pork from Sonora
label: BODY

text: and Yucatan even though other regions of
label: BODY

text: the country are not allowed to export pork
label: BODY

text: to the United States because of the presence
label: BODY

text: of CSF.
label: BODY

text: Plant health ofﬁcials refer to regionalization
label: BODY

text: as “area freedom.” The name is different, but
label: BODY

text: the results are the same. When Pennsylvania
label: BODY

text: ofﬁcials discovered an outbreak of plum pox
label: BODY

text: in October 1999, area freedom kept the
label: BODY

text: entire State, and perhaps the entire Nation,
label: BODY

text: from being quarantined. Under area free-
label: BODY

text: dom, the disease, which infects stone fruit,
label: BODY

text: resulted in a quarantine only in the Adams
label: BODY

text: County, PA, area where plum pox was
label: BODY

text: detected. Other major U.S. stonefruit-
label: BODY

text: producing areas, such as Washington, can
label: BODY

text: continue to export peaches, apricots, plums,
label: BODY

text: and almonds.
label: BODY

text: Should one nation disagree with another’s
label: BODY

text: trade requirements, the requirements can be
label: BODY

text: challenged through NAFTA and the WTO’s
label: BODY

text: dispute settlement processes. A disagree-
label: BODY

text: ment arising between Mexico, Canada, or
label: BODY

text: the United States could be ﬁrst addressed
label: BODY

text: through NAFTA. In both NAFTA and the
label: BODY

text: WTO, a panel is appointed to review the situ-
label: BODY

text: ation and make a ruling. If a country fails to
label: BODY

text: recognize the panel’s ruling, the WTO
label: BODY

text: provides a mechanism for proceeding.

text: International Standards
label: BODY

text: The WTO and NAFTA encourage countries to
label: BODY

text: base their SPS regulations on international
label: BODY

text: standards. Countries are required to publish
label: BODY

text: proposed regulations in order to give other
label: BODY

text: nations a chance to comment before the
label: BODY

text: regulations go into effect. This process is
label: BODY

text: intended to reduce unnecessary variance
label: BODY

text: between countries’ technical health stan-
label: BODY

text: dards—differences that are often the cause
label: BODY

text: of trade disputes. It is a top priority of APHIS
label: BODY

text: to work with our trading partners to develop
label: BODY

text: internationally acceptable standards. We’ve
label: BODY

text: already made great progress in this area with
label: BODY

text: some nations, especially Canada and Mexico.
label: BODY

text: APHIS works with and recognizes a number
label: BODY

text: of standards-setting organizations that help
label: BODY

text: determine the rules for international trade.
label: BODY

text: L’Ofﬁce International des Epizooties
label: BODY

text: (OIE) and Animal Health
label: BODY

text: One of the most important standards-setting
label: BODY

text: organizations, Paris-based OIE has more
label: BODY

text: than 150 member countries. It was started in
label: BODY

text: the 1920’s in response to the appearance of
label: BODY

text: rinderpest in Europe from Pakistan. Each
label: BODY

text: member country has one vote and one dele-
label: BODY

text: gate. Its major functions are to collect and
label: BODY

text: disseminate information on the distribution
label: BODY

text: and control of animal diseases, coordinate
label: BODY

text: research on contagious animal diseases, and
label: BODY

text: standardize rules for international trade in
label: BODY

text: animals and animal products.
label: BODY

text: OIE aims to ensure that scientiﬁcally justi-
label: BODY

text: ﬁed measures are used to govern interna-
label: BODY

text: tional trade in animals and animal products.
label: BODY

text: The WTO has designated the OIE as the
label: BODY

text: international forum for setting animal
label: BODY

text: health standards, reporting global animal
label: BODY

text: health situations and status, and presenting
label: BODY

text: guidelines and recommendations on animal
label: BODY

text: health issues.
label: BODY

text: International and North American
label: BODY

text: Organizations for Plant Health
label: BODY

text: The WTO recognizes the International Plant
label: BODY

text: Protection Convention (IPPC) when it comes
label: BODY

text: to setting plant health standards. In effect
label: BODY

text: since 1952, the IPPC is a multilateral treaty
label: BODY

text: that promotes “. . . common and effective
label: BODY

text: action to prevent the spread and introduc-
label: BODY

text: tion of pests of plants and plant products
label: BODY

text: and to promote measures for their control.”
label: BODY

text: The treaty is administered by the Food and
label: BODY

text: Agriculture Organization (FAO) of the United
label: BODY

text: Nations. Currently, more than 100 countries
label: BODY

text: adhere to the IPPC.
label: BODY

text: In 1989, an IPPC Secretariat was created to
label: BODY

text: coordinate activities for the IPPC and to sup-
label: BODY

text: port the development and administration of
label: BODY

text: international phytosanitary standards. Given
label: BODY

text: the importance of international standards to
label: BODY

text: future agricultural trade, the technical and
label: BODY

text: regulatory nature of plant health issues
label: BODY

text: covered by the IPPC, and APHIS’ scientiﬁc
label: BODY

text: expertise in this area, APHIS has assumed
label: BODY

text: the role of lead U.S. agency participating in
label: BODY

text: activities of the IPPC.
label: BODY

text: The IPPC objectives are to develop interna-
label: BODY

text: tional plant health standards, promote the
label: BODY

text: harmonization of plant quarantine activities
label: BODY

text: with emerging standards, facilitate the dis-
label: BODY

text: semination of phytosanitary information,
label: BODY

text: support plant health assistance to developing
label: BODY

text: countries, and resolve disputes.
label: BODY

text: The North American Plant Protection
label: BODY

text: Organization (NAPPO)—a regional plant
label: BODY

text: protection organization of the IPPC created
label: BODY

text: in 1976—coordinates the efforts among
label: BODY

text: Canada, the United States, and Mexico to
label: BODY

text: protect their plant resources from the entry,
label: BODY

text: establishment, and spread of plant pests
label: BODY

text: while ensuring the free ﬂow of trade between
label: BODY

text: the three nations. APHIS employees are fre-
label: BODY

text: quently assigned to NAPPO committees
label: BODY

text: charged with reviewing technical standards
label: BODY

text: or reviewing new methods for pest control.
label: BODY

text: 4 APHIS in the Global Trade Arena
label: BODY

text: It is a top priority
label: BODY

text: of APHIS to work
label: BODY

text: with our trading
label: BODY

text: partners to develop
label: BODY

text: internationally
label: BODY

text: acceptable
label: BODY

text: standards. We’ve
label: BODY

text: already made
label: BODY

text: great progress
label: BODY

text: in this area with
label: BODY

text: some nations,
label: BODY

text: especially Canada
label: BODY

text: and Mexico.
label: BODY

text: For example, APHIS employees worked with
label: BODY

text: NAPPO to develop guidelines for the release
label: BODY

text: of nonnative organisms to control weeds.
label: BODY

text: In addition to establishing plant quarantine
label: BODY

text: standards, NAPPO also has developed a pest
label: BODY

text: risk analysis (PRA) standard. PRAs are gener-
label: BODY

text: ally done for every agricultural commodity
label: BODY

text: entering the United States. The PRA identi-
label: BODY

text: ﬁes foreign pests that could harm U.S. agri-
label: BODY

text: culture and the level of risk related to a
label: BODY

text: particular commodity. By adhering to the
label: BODY

text: PRA standard developed by NAPPO, the
label: BODY

text: United States, Mexico, and Canada can all be
label: BODY

text: assured they’re using the same approach to
label: BODY

text: evaluate pest risks.
label: BODY

text: Codex and Free Trade Areas
label: BODY

text: for the Americas
label: BODY

text: The Codex Alimentarius Commission for
label: BODY

text: food safety standards is the third interna-
label: BODY

text: tional standards-setting organization recog-
label: BODY

text: nized by the WTO. Jointly managed by the
label: BODY

text: World Health Organization and the FAO,
label: BODY

text: Codex, established in 1963, facilitates world
label: BODY

text: food trade by establishing international stan-
label: BODY

text: dards based on accepted scientiﬁc knowl-
label: BODY

text: edge. Codex deals with subjects such as food
label: BODY

text: additives, pesticide residues, and food label-
label: BODY

text: ing. Codex expert committees are composed
label: BODY

text: of representatives from government regula-
label: BODY

text: tory agencies, such as USDA’s Food Safety
label: BODY

text: and Inspection Service, the international sci-
label: BODY

text: entiﬁc community, and industry.
label: BODY

text: The OIE, IPPC, NAPPO, and Codex have
label: BODY

text: earned prominent roles in determining the
label: BODY

text: substance, direction, priorities, and out-
label: BODY

text: comes of SPS requirements. Domestic
label: BODY

text: groups have grown increasingly aware of
label: BODY

text: these organizations and the importance of
label: BODY

text: their activities, resulting in increased inter-
label: BODY

text: est and expectations concerning the develop-
label: BODY

text: ment, establishment, and amendment of
label: BODY

text: international standards, particularly from
label: BODY

text: the standpoint of dispute resolution.
label: BODY

text: In addition to working with such standards-
label: BODY

text: setting organizations as the OIE, IPPC, and
label: BODY

text: Codex, the United States is also involved in
label: BODY

text: the proposed negotiation of Free Trade Areas
label: BODY

text: for the Americas (FTAA). In January 1995,
label: BODY

text: the United States and 33 governments from
label: BODY

text: Central and South America and the
label: BODY

text: Caribbean established the foundation for the
label: BODY

text: FTAA, making a joint declaration of their
label: BODY

text: commitment to the hemispheric integration
label: BODY

text: of economics and trade by 2005. FTAA has
label: BODY

text: the potential of accelerating greater intra-
label: BODY

text: hemispheric trade, particularly in agricul-
label: BODY

text: ture, given the signiﬁcant role that
label: BODY

text: agriculture plays in the economies of most
label: BODY

text: Latin American and Caribbean countries.
label: BODY

text: The FTAA initiative reﬂects current U.S.
label: BODY

text: trade policy aimed at deepening our trade
label: BODY

text: relations with newly emerging or developing
label: BODY

text: economies of our hemisphere.
label: BODY

text: As a result of WTO and the pending FTAA,
label: BODY

text: Latin America has evolved into an important
label: BODY

text: region in terms of new markets for U.S.
label: BODY

text: agricultural goods. APHIS has played an
label: BODY

text: instrumental role in establishing trade
label: BODY

text: relationships with these countries.
label: BODY

text: APHIS in the Global Trade Arena 5
label: BODY

text: Asia–Paciﬁc Economic Cooperation
label: BODY

text: Another example of U.S. efforts to broaden
label: BODY

text: commercial relations beyond Europe and
label: BODY

text: Canada is APHIS’ participation in the Asia–
label: BODY

text: Paciﬁc Economic Cooperation (APEC). APEC
label: BODY

text: was established in 1989 to promote coopera-
label: BODY

text: tion in trade and other economic issues.
label: BODY

text: What started out as an organization with
label: BODY

text: 12 member countries has nearly doubled in
label: BODY

text: size to encompass countries as diverse as
label: BODY

text: Australia, Brunei, and China. As a member of
label: BODY

text: APEC, the United States attends regular
label: BODY

text: meetings to discuss such issues as trade lib-
label: BODY

text: eralization, technology transfer, investment,
label: BODY

text: energy, and other topics of mutual interest.
label: BODY

text: It was not until 1995, however, that APEC
label: BODY

text: members agreed to address agricultural
label: BODY

text: trade. At this time, a group of agricultural
label: BODY

text: technical experts was formed to discuss
label: BODY

text: issues, including biotechnology and quaran-
label: BODY

text: tine and pest management.
label: BODY

text: APHIS recognizes the countries in the
label: BODY

text: Paciﬁc Rim region as strategically important
label: BODY

text: agricultural markets and plays a key role in
label: BODY

text: meetings of the APEC agricultural technical
label: BODY

text: experts. In recent years, APHIS has worked
label: BODY

text: hard to develop technical working relation-
label: BODY

text: ships with such nations as Japan, South
label: BODY

text: Korea, and China. These relationships have
label: BODY

text: been instrumental in creating new markets
label: BODY

text: for U.S. agricultural commodities. APHIS
label: BODY

text: was successful in March 2000 with helping
label: BODY

text: to open up the Chinese market to U.S. citrus.
label: BODY

text: Besides being economically signiﬁcant, this
label: BODY

text: agreement also helps pave the way for future
label: BODY

text: market opportunities.
label: BODY

text: Without the creation of the WTO and
label: BODY

text: NAFTA, such trade relationships would not
label: BODY

text: be possible. It’s a principal role of APHIS to
label: BODY

text: make sure the United States and our trading
label: BODY

text: partners adhere to the SPS rules set forth by
label: BODY

text: the WTO and NAFTA as well as the other
label: BODY

text: relevant standards-setting organizations.
label: BODY

text: While trade agreements have helped to open
label: BODY

text: up new markets for the United States and
label: BODY

text: other countries, APHIS must ensure that
label: BODY

text: U.S. agriculture is protected in all endeavors
label: BODY

text: and that agricultural imports from foreign
label: BODY

text: countries do not create new pathways for
label: BODY

text: pests. APHIS’ role in the global marketplace
label: BODY

text: will continue to increase as the United
label: BODY

text: States expands current trade relationships
label: BODY

text: and establishes new partnerships with
label: BODY

text: developing countries.
